As an instructor at local community college, I face a lot of competition as I am trying to deliver my lessons. It's not students talking, students doodling in their notebooks, or even students unabashedly taking a nap during my lectures. It's cellphones. Cell phones should be banned from college classrooms.
One reason cell phones should be banned is because of the distraction they cause to me. It's not uncommon for my lectures to be interrupted by sappy country western singers, an annoying buzzing or even the typical phone ring. I have to stop and tell the phone offender to turn off the phone. Their phone has caused an interruption in the flow of the lecture, and I'm not happy.
Another reason cell phones should be banned is because of the distraction it causes to other students. Of course a phone going off is much more interesting than my lecture, so all students turn to find the source of the phone. They are squirming to see who is going to get in trouble. The offender is desperately grabbing for the phone to turn it off, so he or she is not difficult to find.
Lastly, cell phones should be banned because they are a distraction to the actual phone owner. Students seem so addicted to their phones, that they almost go through a withdrawal of sorts if they aren't on them for minutes on end. I have seen panicked looks as I command the students to put away their phones. It's as if I have asked them to give up oxygen for an hour or two.
On the other hand, some will argue that cell phones are useful for students. They believe cell phones are a tool. After all, students can use their phones as a calculator. They can look up unknown vocabulary words. They can find a math formula to help them work a difficult problem. All of this help right at hand, so to speak.
I do understand that cell phones can be helpful if used in the right way. Perhaps there could be an time set aside during class that would allow students to use their phone. It would be a phone break, so to speak. I can see it now-it would be a room full of students with heads down, fingers flying, and eyes

lued to the screen as if there was nothing else in the world around them.\nI know I am not going to win the cell phone war any time soon. I've banned them, collected them, made jokes about them, and simply ignored them. In the end, I have found nothing works. So, I just go ahead and give my lectures fully expecting the beeps, rings and sappy country western singers to interrupt my exciting lectures.
we have become immune to it.
